{"id":14882017,"mediaExerciseId":"f78f5267-3380-4fc9-9058-67fd8d249f58","exerciseName":"7","chapterName":"27","chapterTitle":"Leasing","groupId":612532,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":909,"solutions":[{"id":6504126,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This task aims to explain off-balance sheet financing and leasing contracts.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"\nThe term **off-balance sheet financing** refers to the accounting practice that companies had of not reporting the use of a leased asset on the balance sheet, only reporting the lease in footnotes to the balance sheets. \n\nNow, let's recall the two types of leases we have leared in this section: Capital lease and Operating lease. \n\nThe Financial Accounting Standards Board issues a standard for including capital lease information on the balance sheet at least for capital lease, where the lease payments must be capitalized as a liability, and the leased asset appears as an asset. \n\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"***What are the potential problems with using off-balance sheet financing for leases?***\n\nThe study of financial health through financial ratios is largely determined through the balance sheet. **Off-balance sheet** leases can give a blurred picture of the company's debt ratios.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"a2b328ca-a0c1-4b58-83b8-9889a8c524bc","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq